{
  "text": "Definition 4.1. (Identifiable and non identifiable Machines) Let (\u2126, F, P ) be a probability space and let P (y|x, \u03c9) be the probabilistic inference or prediction probability of a statistical machine, where y \u2208 R n is an output vector and x \u2208 R m is an input vector. If \u03c9 \u2192 P (y|x, \u03c9) is an injective mapping is we say the machine is identifiable, see Watanabe [CITATION_1] . If the mapping is not injective, then we say that the machine is a non identifiable machine.",
